    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Instruments pierced with a hole, used in pre-Columbian times for the purpose of "seeing". Literally, "That by which one sees". Attribute of several deities such as Tezcatlipoca and Xiuhteuctli. According to the sources, could have been made of gold, in mosaic of feathers. Sometimes compared to a mirror.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Literalmente, "aquello por lo que se ve", que se refiere a un instrumento perforado con un agujero, a veces comparado con un espejo. Un atributo de varias deidades como Tezcatlipoca y Xiuhteuctli. A menudo estaba hecho de oro o de un mosaico de plumas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
